5–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Matilda was born in 1194, in Pembrokeshire, Wales. She had at least 1 daughter with Sir Thomas II Le Waleys, Baron Waleys of Pembroke. She died in 1242, in Wales, United Kingdom, at the age of 48."},"et":{"1194–1242":"1194–1242","1194–1219":"1194–1219","1224–1315":"1224–1315","1315":"1315","about 1219":"umbes 1219","1224":"1224","1242":"1242","1194":"1194","1219":"1219","Manor Eglys, Cwmmin, Pembroke, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, United Kingdom","Pembroke Castle, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembroke Castle, Pembrokeshire, Wales","Manor and Rake, Flintshire, Wales":"Manor and Rake, Flintshire, Wales"},"fi":{"1194–1242":"1194–1242","1194–1219":"1194–1219","1224–1315":"1224–1315","1315":"1315","about 1219":"noin 1219","1224":"1224","1242":"1242","1194":"1194","1219":"1219","Manor Egly